tasks.content: Now that our application is starting to take shape, we’ll be gradually adding new pages to it. Don’t worry if you already see them on my end — for now, I just want to outline which page corresponds to which lesson. This will help you better understand the structure of the app and get a clearer feel for the flow of the course.
Here’s the plan showing which page is linked to each lesson.
Before we move on to describing each page, please note that my “Page 6” (6) is not visible in the application. This is indicated by the crossed-out eye icon — “Hide from menu” (8).

Why is that? I used this page for testing various functionalities, and it has been intentionally hidden — both in the app and throughout the course. You don’t need to create it or worry about it. I’m just mentioning it to clarify things, so you don’t feel like anything is missing.

This is the page where users can easily search for information about ski slopes — their names, difficulty levels, and filter results based on their preferences. For example, if someone is talking to a friend over the phone who gives them the name of a slope, instead of searching for it on a printed map (which are often handed out at ski resorts), they can simply type the name in the app and find it right away. It serves as a functional hub for searching and filtering slope data.

The main purpose of this page is to demonstrate the use of the Timeline widget. In our case, we’re not using actual real-time data, but ideally, this card would represent that type of functionality. In a real-world scenario, you could connect it to a live data source and set it to refresh at regular intervals — this is entirely doable.
For the course, however, our focus is on practicing how to work with the Timeline widget itself, which is used to visualize time-based data.
If you'd like to configure your own data, you can check out:
Lecture: Publishing data from ArcGIS Pro – Timeline (available in the Additional Content section)

This is our main entry page — essentially, the app’s business card. That’s why we’ll keep coming back to this page throughout the course. We want the learning experience to stay engaging and varied, not just step-by-step.

Why is this important? Because for the Home page (1) to be interactive, we first need to configure the other pages. For example, if we want a list on the homepage to filter data shown on Page 4, we must set up Page 4 correctly first — it’s just logical.

So don’t worry if we revisit the homepage several times — that’s actually how real-world app development works: refining and polishing the landing page to make it as clear, helpful, and visually appealing as possible for the end user.
For instance, in the lesson about the Card widget, we’ll return to the Home page to enhance its design and layout.
Lecture: Interactivity of the application – URL

This page helps users evaluate whether a particular ski valley suits their skill level and preferences. Through statistical summaries, users can see if there are enough slopes that match their snowboarding or skiing ability in a given region.

It’s especially useful when deciding which valley to choose — whether they’re looking for an easier, more relaxed area or seeking bigger challenges and longer runs. This page acts as an interactive analysis tool to support smart decision-making based on real data.
Lecture: Select – Introduction to Framework (Summer mode)

In this part of the course, we’ll be using ArcGIS Dashboards and learning how to apply parameters. Parameters are extremely useful for creating dynamic and optimized applications. They help streamline your Experience Builder setup and can save a significant amount of time when configuring or updating interactive elements.

Unlike the previous page (Page 4), which provided a general overview of the ski valleys (such as total slope length or share of ski lifts), this page focuses on a more detailed analysis of a selected valley.

Once the user selects a specific valley, they can explore the distribution of slopes by difficulty level — for example, how many green, blue, red, or black slopes there are. This helps users better assess whether the valley meets their skill level and preferences.
To visualize this information, we’ll use the Charts widget, which will be explained in detail in this section of the course.

The “Your Feedback” page is designed to allow users to share their experience from their stay at the resort — in this case, the Three Valleys in France. This feedback provides the app creator with valuable insights into how satisfied visitors were with the location and services.

The main focus here is on integrating Survey123, a powerful survey tool within ArcGIS Online. You'll learn how to embed a survey form into your Experience Builder app, how to use GlobalID fields, and how to generate personalized feature reports in PDF format based on the responses.
Congratulations! If you've made it this far, you’ve shown incredible determination, and I admire your commitment!
Now you finally understand the concept we have for finishing this shared journey of creating an app in Experience Builder!

It’s time to design, refine, and ensure that all the pages and features are fully functional and attractive to users. Every step we’ve discussed is an important part of the whole puzzle, but the real magic happens when you start combining them into a finished product.
Have you thought through your app concept and how all the elements will work together? Remember, app development is a process that can always be improved and adapted to meet user needs.
Now, together, we will move on to designing and creating your app, making it fully interactive and ready for use!

Later in the course, page (7) will be frequently explored and changed by me, but don’t worry about it. For us, the final stage of the journey will be Chapter 7. However, the course has been divided more according to the content of the Experience Builder app because I want you to come back to the course even after completing it! You’ll be able to quickly recall a specific part of the app or what you're currently configuring, and easily understand how a particular widget works.
